b'' b'' b"anyone who thinks that tiff is too complex hasn't dealt with" b'cgm, asn.1, cda, dca, sgml, or any one of a number of other' b'very successful file format. people seem perfectly capable' b'dealing with these others. dealing with the format of tiff' b'is frankly less difficult than dealing with the dct, lzw, and' b'fax encoding of the image data. the majority of the libraries' b'which deal with tiff are dedicated to these other issues rather' b'than with simply decoding the tags and parameters.' b'' b'perhaps people are overwhelmed in comparison with some rather' b'simpleminded formats such as gif, pcx, and bmp, but to suggest' b'that tiff is so complex as to be doomed to failure is ludicrous.' b'' b"that doesn't mean that gif isn't fine, but don't even thing about" b'using it in many instances. gif is very nice for use in low-end' b'photos applications and for screen grabs and such, but it would' b'never do for high-volume or high-resolution systems. fax is nice,' b"but it doesn't do color (and gif doesn't do b&w all that well)." b'jpeg is nice for high-resolution color, but is slow for low-end.' b'' b'the advantage tiff brings to the table is its ability to handle' b"all these situations (and then some). naturally it's more complex." b"but i'ld rather propose tiff imaging solutions over imaging" b'systems based on having to deal with file formats anyday.' b'' b'you may find that tiff is too complicated for your personal tastes' b"but please don't wrail against it's complexity. the complexity" b'it contains is required to provide the functionality it does and' b"doesn't come close to the complexity found in most commercially" b'viable file formats.' b'' b'' b"if we're in philosophical arguments against complexity, let's all" b'go program in scheme and forth and do imaging with run length' b'encoding.' b'' b'' 